{
  "$schema": "../../schema/pathway.schema.json",
  "id": "gluconeogenesis",
  "name": "Gluconeogenesis",
  "category": "carbohydrate-metabolism",
  "summary": "De novo synthesis of glucose from non-carbohydrate precursors (lactate, pyruvate, glucogenic amino acids, glycerol), bypassing the three irreversible steps of glycolysis with four dedicated enzymes.",
  "description": "Gluconeogenesis synthesizes glucose from three- and four-carbon precursors, chiefly during fasting, starvation, and prolonged exercise, and occurs mainly in the liver and renal cortex (and, in extended fasting, the small intestine). Seven of the ten glycolytic reactions are near-equilibrium and simply run in reverse, but the three exergonic, effectively irreversible glycolytic steps (hexokinase, PFK-1, pyruvate kinase) must be bypassed by four gluconeogenesis-specific enzymes: (1) mitochondrial pyruvate carboxylase converts pyruvate to oxaloacetate and (2) PEP carboxykinase converts oxaloacetate to phosphoenolpyruvate — together bypassing pyruvate kinase; (3) fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase bypasses PFK-1; and (4) glucose-6-phosphatase in the ER lumen bypasses hexokinase. Because oxaloacetate cannot cross the inner mitochondrial membrane, it is exported as malate, which also delivers the cytosolic NADH required by the glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate dehydrogenase step. Making one glucose from two pyruvate is expensive: it consumes 4 ATP, 2 GTP, and 2 NADH. The pathway is reciprocally regulated with glycolysis — allosterically (acetyl-CoA activates pyruvate carboxylase; AMP and fructose-2,6-bisphosphate inhibit FBPase-1) and hormonally/transcriptionally (glucagon and glucocorticoids induce PEPCK and glucose-6-phosphatase; insulin represses them via FOXO1) — so that glycolysis and gluconeogenesis are not fully active at once.",
  "organisms": ["human"],
  "tissues": ["liver", "kidney cortex", "small intestine"],
  "keywords": ["glucose synthesis", "pyruvate carboxylase", "PEPCK", "fructose-1,6-bisphosphatase", "glucose-6-phosphatase", "Cori cycle", "fasting metabolism", "reciprocal regulation"],
